Poem.Petrarchan sonnet:
The ever-growing population's needs demand more food,
And with it, more waste that is not understood.
The quality of what we consume must increase,
To meet the challenge of a changing good.

We seek to revalue this waste and its streams,
To recover the health benefits within.
Though complex in nature, these compounds we glean;
Ionic and hydrophobic interactions. 

Low concentrations make regular processes costly; 
Models are needed to predict behaviour. 
Group Contribution models can reduce complexity; 
Solubility and adsorption are our saviour. 

A “toolbox” of models is now established; 
For soy and tea polyphenols they will serve best. 
These models can be applied to different sources; 
An integrated process we can invest.

In search of insight and understanding, this research sets out to explore
The fuel combustion of liquid in hot-diluted air, a milder flame called MILD.
For model validation to be possible, complete and accurate data must be found;
The Delft Spray-in-Hot-Coflow database is the source that's been found. 

Combining physical insight with numerical methods and software development, 
Three levels of complexity and accuracy have been tested in the CFD framework. 
RANS/SFM was employed first, but it failed to predict lift-off height; 
It was concluded that a TCI model was needed for further insight. 

TPDF and FGM were used next, exploring the dilute spray region; 
Boundary conditions were carefully specified for flow and combustion progression. 
Parametric studies were then carried out to gain useful information; 
Good agreement with experimental data was achieved with adiabatic approximation. 

LES/FGM was used last to study a wide range of test cases; 
Dynamic procedures were developed for auto-ignition prediction.  
CDIM was proposed to take into account flash boiling atomization;  
Enthalpy deficit added as an extra dimension improved gas phase temperature prediction.  

Through these three stages of modeling approaches, understanding has been gained;  
This knowledge will help in design of clean and efficient combustion technology attained.
